            When I went to Gibraltar with Peter Caruana and poked my face through the fence&#x2014;with television cameras and a reporter from the <span class="italic">Gibraltar Chronicle</span>present&#x2014;the cars suddenly went through very quickly. To those hon. Members who say that the only reason the delay was affected was that the Minister of State was visiting, I say that, when I was at the border, people went through very rapidly. However, I am not saying that I would like to go and stand there every week in order to sort out the problem.</p><p>
            As a result of what hon. Members have said today, I shall write again because this is something of which the Commissioner needs to be reminded. It will be appropriate for me to do so, because I have just visited Gibraltar and I can send him the photographs that we took of the waiting cars and ask for action to be taken. However, let us not say what is acceptable and what is not, because if one asked the average citizen sitting in the
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_149wh' title='Col. 149WH &mdash; HC Deb 08 June 2000 vol 351 c149WH' name='column_149wh' href='#column_149wh' rel='bookmark'>149WH</a>
            queue at the border, he or she would say that a delay of five minutes was unacceptable. One must be proportionate.
